      I must study electronic trading so that my son may get into crystals =
and run my ESG department
   =20
 =20
Here=E2=80=99s Thomas Peterffy=E2=80=99s story:Before building a net worth =
of $21.5 billion on Wall Street, Thomas grew up in communist Hungary, immig=
rated to the U.S. at the age of 21 knowing no English, and saved up to buy =
a seat on the American Stock Exchange. He became an early player in electro=
nic trading, building a company that used computers to transact in financia=
l markets and eventually evolved into a broker that sells professional-qual=
ity trading software to individual investors and money managers, including =
hedge funds. He=E2=80=99d achieved the fantasy of amassing an unimaginable =
fortune.Here=E2=80=99s his son  Will Peterffy=E2=80=99s story:He=E2=80=99s =
been a ranch hand in Colorado; an organic farm worker in California; a stud=
ent of yoga, sound therapy, and Chinese medicine; a board member for an env=
ironmental advocacy organization; and a post-production associate for a 10-=
part documentary series on =E2=80=9Carchetypal astrology.=E2=80=9D He serve=
d time at two investment firms, for about nine months apiece, but those sti=
nts left him =E2=80=9Cheart-crushed=E2=80=9D and pushed him in 2016 to go, =
with his dog Bowie, from New York to New Mexico in hopes of absorbing the h=
ealing powers of the desert. =E2=80=A6In late November he visited friends f=
or dinner at their regenerative farm. A citrine crystal, believed to symbol=
ize positivity and new beginnings, sat nearby as he feasted on braised lamb=
 shoulder, mashed potatoes, arugula, beet sauerkraut, and a punchy fermente=
d hot sauce=E2=80=94a meal his friends prepared using only crops and animal=
s raised on their farm, except for a bit of clarified butter and a few glug=
s of olive oil. =E2=80=A6More than two years earlier he=E2=80=99d joined hi=
s father=E2=80=99s company, a giant trading platform called Interactive Bro=
kers Group Inc. Rather than become a sales rep or data analyst, he carved o=
ut a role more simpatico with his worldview. Not unlike when he was 7 and m=
ade the case for getting a pet ferret, he pitched his dad on a big idea: th=
at he could become the company=E2=80=99s first director of environmental, s=
ocial, and governance (ESG) affairs, helping to make the firm a better stew=
ard of the Earth and society. Interactive Brokers would reduce its environm=
ental footprint, boost gender and racial diversity, and, in the triple-bott=
om-line spirit, draw a whole new set of younger customers who want to inves=
t in companies doing the same. =E2=80=9CWe=E2=80=99ve been saturated with t=
his idea that we are separate=E2=80=94we are separate from each other, we a=
re separate from the Earth, we are separate from nature=E2=80=94and it=E2=
=80=99s just not true,=E2=80=9D he says. =E2=80=9CWe=E2=80=99re very connec=
ted with each other. All life is connected. And it=E2=80=99s not even woo-w=
oo.=E2=80=9DAnd he should know what=E2=80=99s woo-woo.=C2=A0I suppose that =
if you make billions of dollars in financial services your kids will have s=
ome tendency to become documentary film producers and look down on financia=
l services as grubby capitalism while cashing checks from their trust funds=
. But ESG is, among other things, a way for financial-services billionaires=
 to bond with their alternative-healing-curious children. =E2=80=9CDad, I=
=E2=80=99ve decided that I don=E2=80=99t want to work in sales or data at t=
he family brokerage, because that is bad capitalism and separates me from n=
ature, but I could be your director of ESG. This idea that your electronic =
brokerage firm is separate from the earth, it=E2=80=99s just not true, I th=
ink that with the right set of crystals I could really=E2=80=94=E2=80=9D =
=E2=80=9CSounds great, Junior, I=E2=80=99m just happy to have you aboard, g=
ive me a hug.=E2=80=9DImagine being the=C2=A0deputy director of ESG at Inte=
ractive Brokers. Presumably you got hired based on your background doing ES=
G initiatives at major financial firms.=C2=A0Presumably you think of ESG as=
 a real career path in finance, and you have spent your career building exp=
ertise in the theory and practice and complex accounting of ESG.=C2=A0But y=
ou=E2=80=99ve got to compete with financial-services heirs, and British-mon=
archy heirs for that matter. ESG is, somewhat paradoxically, an attractive =
area of finance for people who don=E2=80=99t care about finance but do like=
 the money it provides.
