      NFT Stuff
   =20
 =20
I guess a good financial product is a vending machine where (1) you put in =
money and (2) the machine gives you a receipt verifying that you put in the=
 money? I mean. That=E2=80=99s a good financial product for the owner of th=
e machine? I don=E2=80=99t know why you=E2=80=99re putting in the money tho=
ugh. I don=E2=80=99t know anything:It=E2=80=99s easy to miss the storefront=
 that is home to the =E2=80=9Cworld=E2=80=99s first NFT vending machine=E2=
=80=9D in Manhattan=E2=80=99s financial district. Squished between a sandwi=
ch shop and a tailor, the windows are bathed in pink neon light, with glowi=
ng letters that announce =E2=80=9CNFT ATM.=E2=80=9D When you walk through t=
he entryway, you enter a tiny booth with the vending machine, filled with r=
ows of little paper cartons, looking almost like cigarette packs. There are=
 only two products: a =E2=80=9Ccolor=E2=80=9D for $5.99 and a =E2=80=9Cpart=
y pigeon=E2=80=9D for $420.69. ...I didn=E2=80=99t think my editor would be=
 thrilled with the pigeon, so I bought a color. This, it turns out, meant a=
 piece of paper inside the carton with a randomly generated code that would=
 allow me to =E2=80=9Cmint=E2=80=9D an NFT, claiming ownership over one of =
10,000 different colors. Birnholtz tried to clarify: =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s =
impossible to own a color. What you own is a ledger on the Solana blockchai=
n that represents that particular color. And we allow people to collect tho=
se colors to trade them, and sell them.=E2=80=9DThe guy=E2=80=99s NFT didn=
=E2=80=99t even work, but would it have been better if it did? Anyway if yo=
u want to send me $420.69 I=E2=80=99ll send you a randomly generated sequen=
ce of numbers sure why not I can afford that.
