<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Sanctions, etc.</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A week ago Russia was a more or less w=
ell-integrated part of the global financial system. Shares of Russian compa=
nies traded in Europe and the U.S., Russian companies issued bonds to globa=
l investors and did joint ventures with global companies, Russian commoditi=
es were sold abroad for dollars and euros, Russian airlines leased planes f=
rom Irish finance companies, everything was just part of an international w=
eb of contracts and transactions.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It is pos=
sible that, say, a year from now none of that will be true. It is possible =
that Russia will continue invading and occupying Ukraine and killing civili=
ans there, that international sanctions against Russia will continue and be=
come harsher, and that even beyond legal sanctions international companies =
and investors will avoid dealing with Russia due to public pressure or=C2=
=A0worries about risk . And in a year shares of Russian companies will trad=
e only in Russia, Russian companies will not get financing from abroad, the=
re will be no joint ventures, they=E2=80=99ll own their own planes made in =
Russia, etc. (Or, more plausibly, Russia will maintain financial ties to so=
me foreign countries, mainly China, but will be shut out of broader interna=
tional markets.)=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But the <em>transiti=
on </em>between those two states is extremely <a href=3D"https://link.mail.=
bloombergbusiness.com/click/26886847.262605/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmN=
vbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDMtMDIvcnVzc2lhbi1tYXJrZXRzLWJyZWFrLWRvd24td2=
l0aC1jYXNoLWZyb3plbi1hdC10aGUtYm9yZGVyP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAzMDIyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJ=
nV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMDMwMiZ1=
dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBaf9e2567" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
 complicated and uncertain</a>. For instance, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.=
bloombergbusiness.com/click/26886847.262605/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmN=
vbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDMtMDEvbm9ib2R5LXdhbnRzLXJ1c3NpYW4tYXNzZX=
RzP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAzMDIyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZ=
T1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMDMwMiZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f0=
7ceef4b8524a319a23cB548aebe8" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope=
" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importa=
nt; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-s=
tyle: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> we talked yesterday</a> about how in=
ternational oil companies own stakes in Russian joint ventures, and do not =
want to own them anymore. But who do they sell them to? I wrote about BP Pl=
c=E2=80=99s plan to exit its joint venture with Rosneft PJSC:</p><blockquot=
e><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I suppose you could donate them back to the =
company =E2=80=94=C2=A0call up Rosneft and say =E2=80=9Ccancel our shares, =
don=E2=80=99t bother paying us=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0but I am not sure th=
at that=E2=80=99s a good way to impose sanctions=C2=A0<em>on Russia</em>; i=
t is in some sense=C2=A0<em>good=C2=A0</em>for Rosneft (or Shell=E2=80=99s =
Russian partners in its joint ventures, etc.) to cancel equity claims on it=
s business=C2=A0for free. If you=E2=80=99re writing the assets down to zero=
 anyway I suppose one option (depending on the mechanics of the sanctions r=
egime) is to give them to charity; there would be something a bit satisfyin=
g about a Ukraine relief charity owning 20% of Rosneft.=C2=A0</p></blockquo=
te><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The realistic answer, though not a great on=
e, is to donate the shares to Rosneft, and apparently <a href=3D"https://li=
nk.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26886847.262605/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21=
iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDMtMDIvZXh4b24tdG8taGFuZC1zdGFrZS1pbi=
1ydXNzaWFuLW9pbC1wcm9qZWN0LXRvLXJvc25lZnQtcGFydG5lcnM_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDMwMjIyX=
01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rl=
cm09MjIwMzAyJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa901e=
8cf" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;"> Exxon is doing that with its JV</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Exxon Mobil Corp. plans to hand over its stake in a Ru=
ssian oil development to Kremlin-controlled Rosneft PJSC and other partners=
 as sanctions make it harder to operate in the country. =E2=80=A6</p><p sty=
le=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Exxon, Rosneft and their Japanese and Indian partner=
s have been harvesting crude from a cluster of subsea fields off the coast =
of Sakhalin Island since 2005. Exxon valued the asset at $4 billion on its =
balance sheet, according to company documents. =C2=A0</p></blockquote><p st=
yle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In some rough accounting sense the result of this d=
ecision is that Exxon is giving Rosneft $4 billion, though that is probably=
 not the right way to look at it in the long run.[1]</p><p style=3D"margin:=
 16px 0;">Or, it is one thing to say =E2=80=9Cinternational investors shoul=
d not buy Russian government bonds,=E2=80=9D but right now international in=
vestors=C2=A0<em>do=C2=A0</em>own Russian government bonds. But they can=E2=
=80=99t sell them, and they=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusi=
ness.com/click/26886847.262605/aHR0cHM6Ly9ibGlua3MuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdz=
L3N0b3JpZXMvUjg0NllTVDFVTTE1P2NtcGlkPUJCRDAzMDIyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWR=
pdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMDMwMiZ1dG1fY2FtcG=
FpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB00360ea2" itemprop=3D"StoryLi=
nk" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text=
-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color=
: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">can=E2=80=
=99t get paid</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Russia paid =
a=C2=A0coupon=C2=A0due on ruble bonds on Wednesday, but it=E2=80=99s not cl=
ear how foreigners will be able to access the cash after the central bank b=
anned transfers to foreign investors.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Inves=
tors are still scrambling to understand whether or not the bonds could be i=
n default even after the 11 billion ruble ($98 million) payment that was wi=
dely expected. The Bank of Russia has introduced capital controls in a bid =
to avert a ruble collapse after its foreign reserves were frozen by interna=
tional governments in response to Russia=E2=80=99s invasion of Ukraine.=C2=
=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The restrictions could leave foreign in=
vestors who held almost 3 trillion rubles ($29 billion) in the so-called OF=
Z debt at the start of February unable to collect income on their holdings =
-- raising the specter of the nation=E2=80=99s first debt default since 199=
8. The transfer of the coupon was=C2=A0reported=C2=A0Wednesday afternoon on=
 the website of the National Settlement Depositary. =C2=A0=C2=A0</p><p styl=
e=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CUnless it reaches all holders, they can=E2=
=80=99t deny default,=E2=80=9D=C2=A0Paul McNamara, a portfolio manager at G=
AM Investments, said of the coupon on Wednesday. =E2=80=9CThey can=E2=80=99=
t say they paid with any conviction.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0=
;">In addition to a broader presidential decree on capital controls on Mond=
ay, the central bank communicated separately to brokers that there would be=
 a temporary ban on the transfer of payments abroad. The regulator subseque=
ntly confirmed the decision in an emailed comment to Bloomberg. On Monday, =
the Interfax news service reported the suspension will be in effect for hal=
f a year unless the regulator lifts it ahead of time.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"=
margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CIssuers have the right to make decisions on the p=
ayment of dividends and the making of other payments on securities and tran=
sfer them to the accounting system,=E2=80=9D the central bank said in an em=
ailed reply to questions on Tuesday. =E2=80=9CHowever, the payments themsel=
ves will not be made by depositories and registrars to foreign clients. Thi=
s also applies to OFZ.=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;=
">Basically the way bond interest works is that the issuer (the Russian gov=
ernment or a=C2=A0Russian company) wires some money at one end, and the bon=
d holder gets wired the money at the other end, and in between there is a s=
eries of intermediaries (trustees, banks, depositories, brokers) who pass t=
he payments along. Right now, broadly speaking, the intermediaries in Russi=
a are not allowed to pass payments along to foreigners.=C2=A0</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Meanwhile the main intermediaries=C2=A0<em>outside=C2=
=A0</em>Russia are also starting to decline payments from Russia:</p><block=
quote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The world=E2=80=99s biggest settlement s=
ystems Euroclear and Clearstream are no longer handling Russian assets -- r=
eversing the=C2=A0much-heralded=C2=A0opening of the local debt market to in=
ternational investors nine years ago.=C2=A0</p></blockquote><p style=3D"mar=
gin: 16px 0;">Though this door is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbus=
iness.com/click/26886847.262605/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2F=
ydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDMtMDIvZ2F6cHJvbS1zYWlkLXRvLWJlLWluLXByb2Nlc3Mtb2YtcGF5aW=
5nLWRvbGxhci1ib25kcy1kdWUtbWFyY2gtNz9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMzAyMjJfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1d=
G1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMjAzMDImdXRt=
X2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBf1b99a4e" itemprop=3D"=
StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #00000=
0; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-botto=
m-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> not=
 closing entirely</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Gazprom =
PJSC, the Russian state-controlled energy giant, is already in the process =
of settling a $1.3 billion debt due on Monday.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px =
0;">The company wired the cash on Feb. 28 to the settlement bank, which wil=
l probably release the funds on March 4, a person familiar with the matter =
said, declining to be identified because the information is private. Gazpro=
m also has a coupon payment nominally due a day earlier on a Swiss franc de=
bt, which the person said will also be paid.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;=
">It=E2=80=99s a reprieve for Gazprom=E2=80=99s bonds, which lost about hal=
f of their value in just over a week as investors fretted over whether the =
company will settle next week=E2=80=99s payments.=C2=A0</p></blockquote><p =
style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Observers of sovereign debt crises might remember=
=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26886847.262=
605/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTUtMDMtMTM=
vbm93LWFyZ2VudGluYS1jYW4tdC1ldmVuLXBheS1ib25kcy1pbi1hcmdlbnRpbmE_Y21waWQ9Qk=
JEMDMwMjIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0Z=
XImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIwMzAyJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a31=
9a23cBa4508b4f" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_b=
lank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bot=
tom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; b=
ackground-color: #ccc;">Argentina=E2=80=99s 2014 debt default</a>: Argentin=
a had the money to pay interest on its bonds, and wanted to pay interest on=
 its bonds, and it actually showed up at the bank (in Argentina) with the m=
oney, but a New York federal court had prohibited various intermediaries fr=
om transferring the money from Argentina to the holders.[2]=C2=A0At first t=
his struck Argentina, and the intermediaries, and the holders, as somewhat =
absurd, but the judge was serious, the money didn=E2=80=99t get transferred=
, and Argentina defaulted on its debts until it could mollify the New York =
judge and he freed up the payments intermediaries. Here there are a lot of =
relevant authorities and it is hard to see them all being satisfied enough =
to avoid any defaults.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Argentina crisis=
 also notably featured a seizure of an Argentine naval vessel as purported =
collateral for the country=E2=80=99s foreign debts. Here are <a href=3D"htt=
ps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26886847.262605/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cu=
d2FzaGluZ3RvbnBvc3QuY29tL3BvbGl0aWNzLzIwMjIvMDMvMDEvY291bGQtY29uZ3Jlc3MtbGV=
0LXlvdS1zZWl6ZS10aGlzLXJ1c3NpYW4tb2xpZ2FyY2hzLXlhY2h0Lw/607f07ceef4b8524a31=
9a23cB6eaad371" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_b=
lank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bot=
tom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; b=
ackground-color: #ccc;">some nautical seizure claims about the current cris=
is</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Buried in Article I, Se=
ction 8 of the U.S. Constitution is a federal power that will probably be u=
nfamiliar to a layperson. Among the powers granted Congress, it reads, is t=
hat to =E2=80=9Cgrant Letters of Marque and Reprisal, and make Rules concer=
ning Captures on Land and Water.=E2=80=9D So what does that mean? It means =
the federal government is authorized by the Constitution to issue documents=
 (letters of marque) that empower private individuals to legally seize fore=
ign vessels.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On Monday, Rep. Lance Gooden (=
R-Tex.) introduced the idea once again in the context of the yachts and jet=
s owned by those oligarchs. In broad strokes, the theory is that the govern=
ment would establish a system allowing private individuals to seize the ves=
sels and, eventually, make them their own. So instead of that Ukrainian mec=
hanic sinking his Russian boss=E2=80=99s yacht, he could theoretically have=
 gotten some friends together, sailed it away from port and become its new =
owner.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You can see how there might be some =
legal questions here.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I do not=
