uPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB93534dec" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" =
itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-dec=
oration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0=
00000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Bloomberg =E2=
=80=9COdd Lots=E2=80=9D podcast with Zoltan Poszar</a>; from the episode su=
mmary:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Russia=E2=80=99s invasio=
n of Ukraine could mark the beginning of a turning point for the U.S. dolla=
r, according to money market guru Zoltan Pozsar.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16p=
x 0;">Speaking on Bloomberg=E2=80=99s Odd Lots podcast, the global head of =
short-term interest rate strategy at Credit Suisse AG noted that wars tend =
to turn into major junctures for global currencies, and with Russia losing =
access to its foreign currency reserves, a message has been sent to all cou=
ntries that they can=E2=80=99t count on these money stashes to actually be =
theirs in the event of tension. As such, it may make less and less sense fo=
r global reserve managers to hold dollars for safety, given that they could=
 be taken away right when they=E2=80=99re most needed.</p></blockquote><p s=
tyle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And here is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomberg=
business.com/click/26886847.262605/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZnQuY29tL2NvbnRlbnQvZTU3=
MzUzNzUtNzVkZi00ODU5LWJiZjAtYWUyMmU0ZmUyZmY2/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB60d26=
f31" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;">Rana Foroohar arguing</a> that one consequence of Russia=E2=80=
=99s invasion of Ukraine =E2=80=9Cwill be a quickening of the shift to a bi=
polar global financial system =E2=80=94 one based on the dollar, the other =
on the renminbi.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here on the other=
 hand is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26886847.=
262605/aHR0cHM6Ly9mdWxsc3RhY2tlY29ub21pY3MuY29tL2ZpdmUtcmVhc29ucy10aGUtc2Fu=
Y3Rpb25zLWFyZS13b3JraW5nLw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB83efd321" itemprop=3D"S=
toryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000=
; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom=
-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Alan =
Cole arguing that it is unlikely</a>:=C2=A0</p><blockquote><p style=3D"marg=
in: 16px 0;">The U.S. has substantial reserves of credibility to draw on he=
re. Few dollar users, if any, are likely to commit the same offenses as Rus=
sia or draw the same punishment. Furthermore, as European allies have joine=
d the effort, there aren=E2=80=99t alternatives to the U.S. system.</p><p s=
tyle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In freezing reserves and oligarch assets retroacti=
vely while allowing future oil transactions to go through, the U.S. and Eur=
opean governments may succeed at a kind of policy coup, where some of Russi=
a=E2=80=99s past accumulated wealth from oil exports gets confiscated, and =
yet, it still suffers no incentive to stem future oil production. =E2=80=A6=
</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Financial commentators love talking about =
the dollar losing its status as reserve currency, because it gives them a p=
ermission structure to wildly speculate. But there is little constituency f=
or a Russia-friendly financial system among the world=E2=80=99s largest eco=
nomies. And for countries seeking a relatively neutral and rules-based syst=
em free of geopolitics, China isn=E2=80=99t a very good alternative anyway.=
 (It has a variety of idiosyncratic foreign policy demands of its own, and =
regularly uses economic might to help reinforce them.)</p></blockquote><tab=
le class=3D"liveintent-flex-ad" border=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0" cellspacing=
=3D"0" align=3D"center">
